# Function to display useful tips and commands
tips() {
  case "$1" in
    byobu|tmux)
      cat << EOF
Vim:
  :set paste  - To paste without auto-indent issues

Byobu/Tmux:
  Your custom prefix is: Ctrl+Space

  To start another separate byobu/tmux session, run 'tmx2 new-session -d -s MyNewSessionName'. Then use '<prefix> s' to list sessions and switch, or '<prefix> (' and '<prefix> )' to cycle.
  tmx2 new-session -d -s MyNewSessionName - Start a new detached session

  Common Keybindings (use with <prefix>):
    <prefix> c: Create a new window (opens next to the current one) (Custom)
    <prefix> n: Move to the next window.
    <prefix> p: Move to the previous window.
    <prefix> <: Open pane splitting submenu
    <prefix> >: Open window swapping submenu
    <prefix> [0-9]: Switch directly to window number 0-9.
    <prefix> d: Detach from the session.
    <prefix> %: Split the current pane vertically.
    <prefix> ": Split the current pane horizontally.
    <prefix> ,: Rename the current window.
    <prefix> [: Enter copy/scrollback mode.
      - In copy mode: Use PageUp/PageDown, C-u/C-d, or arrow keys to navigate.
    <prefix> ?: Show keybindings.
    <prefix> z: Toggle zoom for the current pane.

  Pane Navigation:
    <prefix> + Left: Move to the pane on the left.
    <prefix> + Right: Move to the pane on the right.
    <prefix> + Up: Move to the pane above.
    <prefix> + Down: Move to the pane below.
    <prefix> q: Display pane numbers temporarily.
    <prefix> {: Swap current pane with the previous pane.
    <prefix> }: Swap current pane with the next pane.
    <prefix> x: Close the current pane.


  Pane Resizing:
    <prefix> + Alt + Left: Make the current pane wider (if vertical split) or taller (if horizontal split).
    <prefix> + Alt + Right: Make the current pane narrower (if vertical split) or shorter (if horizontal split).
    <prefix> + Alt + Up: Make the current pane taller.
    <prefix> + Alt + Down: Make the current pane shorter.

  Window Management:
    <prefix> .: Move the current window to the next available index.
    exit: Close the current pane or window.
    <prefix> w: List all windows in the current session.
    <prefix> q: List all panes in the current window.
    (Windows are renumbered on close - Custom)
EOF
      ;;
    gemini)
      cat << EOF
Gemini CLI Tips:
  /help: Show help message.
  /bug: Report a bug.
  !: Prefix with ! to run a shell command (e.g., !ls -l).
  Ctrl + J: Add a newline to your input.

  Input Box Navigation (Mac Keyboard in Byobu):
    Ctrl + E: Go to the end of the current line.
    Cmd + Left Arrow: Go to the beginning of the current line.
    Cmd + Right Arrow: Go to the end of the current line.
    Cmd + Up Arrow: Go to the beginning of the entire input text.
    Cmd + Down Arrow: Go to the end of the entire input text.
  (Note: Byobu uses Ctrl + A as its prefix, so standard Ctrl + A for beginning of line is not available.)
EOF
      ;;
    vi)
      cat << 'EOF'
Here is your "Survival Kit" for the Vim path.

Crucial Rule: In the shell, you are in "Insert Mode" by default. You must hit Esc to use any of these.

--- Navigation (Moving Around) ---

Key         Action
---         ------
h / l       Left / Right
j / k       Down / Up (History)
w           Jump forward by start of word
b           Jump backward by start of word
e           Jump to end of word
0 (zero)    Go to start of line
$           Go to end of line
f + char    Find next occurance of char

Pro Tip: w and b are the most important keys here. Stop holding arrow keys; just tap w a few times to fly across the line.

--- Editing (Changing Text) ---

Key         Action
---         ------
i           Insert before cursor
a           Append after cursor
A           Append at end of line
x           Delete character under cursor
dw          Delete word
cw          Change word
D           Delete to end of line
u           Undo

--- The "Power Move" (Text Objects) ---

This is the specific reason people stick with Vim. You don't edit by characters; you edit by "objects."

Try these combinations (verbs + nouns):

* ciw -> Change Inside Word.
  Scenario: Your cursor is in the middle of a long word like SuperCalifra|gilistic. You want to replace it.
  Action: Type ciw. The whole word vanishes, and you are typing the new word.

* dt" -> Delete Till " (quote).
  Scenario: git commit -m "wrong message here"
  Action: Cursor is on w. Type dt". It deletes everything up to the next quote.

--- Multi-line & Yank/Put/Delete ---

Key         Action
---         ------
yy          Yank (copy) the current line
p           Put (paste) the yanked content AFTER the cursor
P           Put (paste) the yanked content BEFORE the cursor
dd          Delete (cut) the current line
O           Open a new line ABOVE the current line and enter Insert mode
o           Open a new line BELOW the current line and enter Insert mode
V           Enter Visual Line mode (select whole lines)
            While in Visual Line mode:
              j/k     to extend selection up/down
              d       to Delete (cut) selected lines
              y       to Yank (copy) selected lines
EOF
      ;;
    shell|terminal)
      cat << 'EOF'
Terminal / Shell Tips:

  --- History Expansion ---
  !!        : Run the previous command again.
  sudo !!   : Run the previous command again, but with sudo.
  !$        : The last argument of the previous command (e.g. `mkdir mydir` then `cd !$`).
  !prefix   : Run the most recent command starting with 'prefix' (e.g. `!git`).

  --- Vim Mode & Editing ---
  Esc       : Enter Command Mode (where you can use h, j, k, l, w, b, dd, etc.).
  i, a, A   : Return to Insert Mode.
  v         : (In Command Mode) Open the current command in your $EDITOR (nvim).
  Ctrl + X, Ctrl + E : Open the current command in your $EDITOR (works in Insert Mode too).
  Ctrl + R  : Reverse search through history (still the fastest way to find old commands).

  --- Control ---
  Ctrl + L  : Clear the screen.
  Ctrl + C  : Cancel/Interrupt the current command.
  Ctrl + Z  : Suspend the current process (resume with `fg`).
EOF
      ;;
    *)
      echo "Usage: tips [byobu|gemini|vi|shell]"
      ;;
  esac
}

alias c='clear'

# Kill lingering gemini_api_prox processes
clean_gemini_prox() {
    echo "Searching for lingering gemini_api_prox processes..."
    PIDS=$(pgrep -f "gemini_api_prox")

    if [ -z "$PIDS" ]; then
        echo "No gemini_api_prox processes found."
        return 0
    fi

    echo "Found gemini_api_prox PIDs: $PIDS"
    echo "Terminating processes..."
    echo "$PIDS" | xargs kill -9

    # Verify
    sleep 1
    PIDS_AFTER=$(pgrep -f "gemini_api_prox")
    if [ -z "$PIDS_AFTER" ]; then
        echo "Successfully terminated all found gemini_api_prox processes."
    else
        echo "The following gemini_api_prox PIDs still exist: $PIDS_AFTER"
        echo "You may need to investigate further."
    fi
}
